<h2>Event in November 2018</h2>
<h3>The exceptionally warm en dry weather in northern Scandinavia</h3>
<br><br>
After an extreme dry and hot summer, northern Scandinavia experienced a continuation of the unusually warm and dry weather, which also led to below average snow cover. The mean 500 hPa geopotential height over November 2018 showed a remarkable stable area of high pressure over Scandinavia, which is a significant departure from the climatological mean. Also in the surface pattern this anomaly is a striking feature.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2018/Analyse_November_2018_500_hPa_geopotential_height_png.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2018/Analyse_November_2018_500_hPa_geopotential_height_png.png" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/nov2018/Analyse_November_2018_Surface_pressure_png.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2018/Analyse_November_2018_Surface_pressure_png.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Mean 500 hPa geopotential height in November 2018 (left) and surface pressure (right).</em>
<br><br>
The anomaly of the mean sea level pressure over November 2018 showed an well marked maximum up to 10-12 hPa over Scandinavia. This had led to strong descending motions and an almost absence of precipitation. Along the northern flank of this ridge most of the time moist and warm air from the Atlantic determined the very mild conditions. Due to this blocked pattern very strong outbreaks of Artic air did not happen.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/nov2018/Map_mslp_anom.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2018/Map_mslp_anom.png" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/nov2018/Map_geop_anom.png"><img alt="" src="../images/nov2018/Map_geop_anom.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Anomaly mean sea level pressure November 2018 (left) and anomaly of the 500 hPa geopotential height (right).</em>
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for November 2018</h2>
High pressure systems were dominant for the weather in large parts of Central, Eastern and Northern Europe this month, resulting in dry and relatively warm weather. The anomaly of the average temperature in November was exceptionally high in the northern part of Scandinavia (Figure 3). Temperatures were also above average in the southeastern part of Europe and in Italy. The number of warm days (above the 90 percentile of the 1981-2010 average) was around 15 in these regions (Figure 4).
<br><br>
